{p 4 4 2}{cmd:fweight}s and {cmd:aweight}s are allowed; see help {help weights}.


{title:Description}

{p 4 4 2}{cmd:bsciker} computes bootstrap confidence interval for
fixed-bandwidth kernel density estimation. It follows Horowitz (1999) and Hall
(1992) based on undersmoothing the kernel to reduce the bias. {cmd:bsciker}
needs the preliminary installation of {cmd:vkdensity}, which allows to compute
the variance of the kernel estimation and allows to decide the degree of
undersmoothing. 

{p 4 4 2}The syntax of {cmd:bsciker} partly mimics the syntax of the official
{cmd:kdensity} that uses fixed kernel estimation methods.


{title:Options}

{p 4 4 2}Most options for {cmd:bsciker} are the same as for {cmd:kdensity};
see {hi:[R] kdensity}. The specific options are the following:

{p 4 8 2}{cmdab:g:enerate}{cmd:(}{it:newvarx} {it:newvard} {it:newvarb}{cmd:)}
creates four new variables: {it:newvarx} will contain the point of estimation;
{it:newvard} will contain the density estimation; and {it:newvarb_u} and
{it:newvarb_l} will contain the upper and lower bound confidence interval
variable.

{p 4 8 2}{cmd:usmooth(}{it:#}{cmd:)} chooses the degree of
undersmoothing for bootstrap confidence interval estimation. The default value
is 1/4. Increasing this number will result in a smaller bandwidth, i.e., a more
variable and less biased estimation, and vice versa.

{p 4 8 2}{cmd:scott}, {cmd:hardle}, and {cmd:silver} allows you to choose
between three different optimal bandwidths, i.e.,  those proposed by Scott
(1992), H{c a:}rdle (1991), and Silverman (1986). See also {cmd:bandw} 
(Salgado-Ugarte, Shimizu, and Taniuchi 1995b; 1995a; 1993).

{p 4 8 2}{cmd:mbandw}{cmd:(}{it:#}{cmd:)} specifies the bandwidth
manually. It conflicts with {cmd:at()}; hence, they cannot be specified at the
same time.

{p 4 8 2}{cmd:bsrepl}{cmd:(}{it:#}{cmd:)} specifies the number of bootstrap
replications to compute.  The default value is 99, which is good for a first
investigation. However, for a final estimation, it often should be much larger
than 99.

{p 4 8 2}{cmd:bsppts}{cmd:(}{it:#}{cmd:)} specifies the percentage of
estimation points at which to compute the confidence interval. This option is
particularly useful for estimation with many data points, which would make the
confidence interval very lengthy. The default value is 100%.

{p 4 8 2}{cmd:seed}{cmd:(}{it:#}{cmd:)} set the seed of the
bootstrap resampling for replication purposes.

{p 4 8 2}{cmd:up} and {cmd:lp} allow you to specify the upper and lower
percentiles to be computed for confidence interval.  The default values are set
to 95% and 5%, so as to obtain a 90% confidence interval but these values can
be changed at will.

{p 4 8 2}{cmd:percent(}{it:#}{cmd:)} specifies the coverage probability of
the confidence interval.  The default value is set at 95 (meaning 95% 
coverage probability), but it can be changed at will.  If {cmd:up()}, 
{cmd:lp()}, and {cmd:percent()} are specified, {cmd:up()} and {cmd:lp()}
are ignored.

{p 4 8 2}{cmd:gr7} creates the graph using Stata 7 instead of Stata 8 graph
facilities.


{title:Examples}

{p 8 12 2}{cmd:. bsciker maker, g(points density bound) scott bsp(499) usm(.3)}


